    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-08-02T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-08-02T01:00:00-05:00" n="991"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d991">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163 Am 33/257: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The First Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-08-02T15:00:00+09:00"
                            >August 2, 1940—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 3—4:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>262. Canton’s July 30, 4 p.m. to Peiping repeated to the Department,<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d991fn3">Not printed.</note> interference with Southern Baptist
                    Mission hospital.</p>
                <p>The Embassy respectfully recommends that representations be made in Tokyo.<note
                        n="5" xml:id="d991fn5">The Department in its telegram No. 289, August 1, 7
                        p.m., instructed the Embassy in Japan accordingly, and the Ambassador in
                        Japan in his telegram No. 703, August 16, noon, reported on action taken
                        (393.1163 Am 33/253, 260).</note>
                </p>
                <p>This unwarranted and petty interference with an American mission hospital on the
                    specious pretext of “military necessity” appears to be another instance of the
                    present provocative attitude of the Japanese military towards Americans in China
                    mentioned in Peiping’s 253, July 25, 6 p.m.<note n="4" xml:id="d991fn4">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent to the Department. Repeated to Chungking, Canton, Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smyth</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
